# SOC Simulator: Introduction to Phishing

## Objective
- Monitor and analyze real-time alerts.
- Identify and document critical events such as suspicious emails and attachments.
- Create detailed case reports based on your observations to help your team understand the full scope of alerts and malicious activity.

## Tools
- VM (Try Hack Me Security Dashboard)
- Splunk
- Virus Total
- 

## Steps
Task 1: 
- Looked at all 4 cases one by one.
- Read what each alert was about
- Checked what triggered the alert
- Focused on anything that looked off like:
   - weird email addresses
   -  urgent messages
   -  unknown attachments
   -  suspicious links

Task 2: 
- Opened Splunk and checked logs related to the alerts
- Searched for events tied to the user/email/IP in each case
- Looked at patterns like:
   -  repeated login attempts
   - unusual access times
   - strange email activity
- Used Splunk results to confirm if the alert was actually suspicious or just a false positive
- Matched what I saw in Splunk with what was shown in the dashboard

Task 3: 
- Tried to figure out what type of issue each case was (phishing, malware, etc.)
- Looked at what the user was being asked to do in the email/message
- Used VirusTotal when needed to check if links/files looked bad
- Compared the options and picked what made the most sense for each case

Task 4: 
- Wrote each alert like a short case using the 5 W’s:
   - Who was involved (user/account affected)
   - What happened (type of alert or activity)
   - When it happened (from Splunk timestamps/logs)
   - Where it happened (email, endpoint, system)
   - Why it looked suspicious (phishing signs, unusual behavior, etc.)
- Used Splunk and dashboard info to build out each case
- After reviewing, I decided if each alert was:
   - True positive (real malicious/suspicious activity)
   - False positive (legit activity that just triggered an alert)
- Based on that, I also decided if it needed to be:
   - Escalated to higher-level SOC/incident response
   - Or closed if it was not a real threat
- Made sure my decision matched the evidence from Splunk logs and the alert detail

## Results
- Finished all 4 cases in the lab
- Used Splunk to confirm suspicious activity in logs
- Understood how alerts, logs, and security tools connect
- Got better at spotting phishing and validating incidents

## Key Takeaways
- Splunk helps confirm what alerts are actually happening behind the scenes
- Not every alert is malicious — logs help verify
- Security works best when combining dashboard alerts + log analysis + endpoint tools

